//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: has no loop to act on
//
// A lambda is lifted into its own function, so control flow cannot cross out of it —
// and the checker has to agree, because at run time there is no enclosing frame left
// to jump to. Every one of these compiled before, and each escaped differently:
//
//   `return`   was checked against the *enclosing function's* return type, so a `str`
//              could be returned through an `i64` slot. It compiled clean and printed
//              garbage — the only memory-unsafe one.
//   `throw`    was absorbed by an enclosing `try`, so the checker called the error
//              handled while it escaped uncaught at run time.
//   `break`    resolved to an enclosing loop and reached `unreachable`.
//
// `return` from a lambda is still fine — it returns from the *lambda*, which is what
// lowering does. See closures/lambda_local_return.neon.

use std::io;

fn run(f: (i64) -> i64) -> i64 { f(1) }

fn main() {
    let total = 0;
    for i in range(0, 3) {
        total = total + run((x: i64) => { break; 0 });
    };
    io::println("#{total}");
}
